    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-05-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-05-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="299"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d299">
                <head>299. Memorandum From Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_LMR1"
                        type="from">Laird</persName> to President <persName type="to"
                        >Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d299fn1">Source: Ford Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_LMR1">Laird</persName> Papers, Box 26, <gloss
                            target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss>, Chronological File. Top Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1972-05-24">May 24, 1972</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Submarine-launched Ballistic Missile Launcher Limits</item>
                </list>
                <p>The Soviets are continuing to resist our proposal to limit <gloss
                        target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss> launchers to a total of 950. They are arguing
                    that our definition of the term “under construction” is inappropriate, and they
                    are asserting that they have 48 “modern” submarines operational and under
                    construction. We estimate that they have between 41 and 43 such submarines
                    operational and under construction. The effect of the Soviet approach is to
                    allow them to reach the 950 level without replacing the 100 <gloss
                        target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss> launchers in <gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>
                    and <gloss target="#t_H1">H</gloss> class submarines. In effect, they are
                    converting an issue on <gloss target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss> launcher levels
                    into a technical issue on how we define such terms as “under construction” and
                    “modern” submarines.</p>
                <p>I believe the inequalities in the offense agreement that would result from <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">U.S</gloss>. proposals are as large as we can tolerate. I
                    strongly recommend therefore that the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S</gloss>.
                    continue to insist that the total number of <gloss target="#t_SLBM1"
                        >SLBM</gloss> launchers on the Soviet side be limited to 950 and that the
                    number of missile launching submarines be limited to 62. This matter should be
                    pressed at the summit if necessary.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LMR1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Melvin R. Laird</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
